quran[19]{c,v,t}:
  38,43,"And We gave him back his family and doubled them—a mercy from Us and a reminding for those endowed with understanding."
  38,44,"“And take with your<sup>sg </sup>hand a bundle of grass, and strike with it so as not to breach<i>(your oath) </i>.” Indeed, We found him patient. What an excellent servant; indeed, he often turns<sup>a </sup>unto Us.",footnotes:1:[Frequently the Qur’an speaks about the prophets using present tense; this should be pondered by the reader.]
  38,45,"And recall<sup>sg </sup>Ourservants{1}Abraham and Isaac and Jacob—those endowed with strong faith and with sight<i>(s) </i>.",footnotes:1:[Qira’at: Ibn Kathir read it as: “And recall<sup><small>sg</small></sup> Our servant Abraham…”]
  38,46,"Surely We distinguished them with a distinct quality{1}—the remembranceof the<i>(final) </i>Home.",footnotes:1:[Qira’at: Nafie’, Hisham and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…with the distinct quality of the remembrance…”]
  38,47,"And indeed, to Us they are of the elect, the outstanding."
  38,48,"And recall<sup>sg </sup>Ishmael and Elisha and Ezekiel—and all are of the outstanding."
  38,49,"This is a Reminder. For indeed, for the mindful<i>(of God) </i>is a beautiful place to return to:"
  38,50,"the Gardens of Eden, with their doors wide-open for them,"
  38,51,"relaxing therein and calling for abundant fruit and beverage."
  38,52,"And with them are bashful maidens of equal age."
  38,53,"This is what you{1}are promisedfor the Day of Reckoning.",footnotes:1:[Qira’at: Ibn Kathir and Abu Amr read it as: “This is what they are promised…”]
  38,54,"Indeed, such is Our provision, inexhaustible."
  38,55,"All this. But indeed, for those who exceed all limits is a miserable place to return to:"
  38,56,"Hell, in which they roast—so what a miserable resting place!"
  38,57,"All this, so let them taste it—scalding water and purulence."
  38,58,"And another{1}<i>(torment) </i>similar to it, of diverse kinds.",footnotes:1:[Qira’at: Abu Amr and Ya’qub read it as: “And other (torments) similar…”]
  38,59,"“This is a crowd rushing headlong with you<sup>pl </sup>.” They are not welcome; indeed, they are to be roasted in the Fire."
  38,60,"They said, “But it is you<sup>pl </sup>who are not welcome! It is you who brought it upon us! So what a miserable end!”"
  38,61,"They said, “Our Lord, whoever brought this upon us, give him double punishment in the Fire.”"
